pullRequest.body:
Generalize the conditions of the tower law [FiniteDimensional.finrank_mul_finrank'](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/FieldTheory/Tower.html#FiniteDimensional.finrank_mul_finrank') in FieldTheory/Tower from `[CommRing F] [Algebra F K]` to `[Ring F] [Module F K]`, and remove the `[Module.Finite F K]` and `[Module.Finite K A]` conditions.

The generalized version applies to situations when we have a tower C/B/A where the A-module structure on C is induced from the B-module structure via a RingHom from A to B, and the A-module structure on B is induced by the same RingHom. In particular, it applies when the A-module structure on B and the B-module structure on C come from two RingHoms, and the A-module structure on C comes from the composition of them, regardless of whether A and B are commutative or not.

As prerequisites, I also generalized lemmas originally introduced by @kckennylau in [mathlib3#3355](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/pull/3355/files) to prove the tower law. They were split into three PRs:

+ LinearAlgebra/Span #9380: add `span_eq_closure` and `closure_induction` which say that `Submodule.span R s` is generated by `R â€¢ s` as an AddSubmonoid. I feel that the existing `span_induction` should be replaced by `closure_induction` as the latter is stronger, and allow us to remove the commutativity condition in `span_smul_of_span_eq_top` in Algebra/Tower.

+ Algebra/Tower #9382: switching from CommSemiring/Algebra to Semiring/Module here requires proving the curious lemma `IsScalarTower.isLinearMap` which states that for a tower of modules A/S/R, any S-linear map from S to A is also R-linear. If the map is injective, we can deduce that S/S/R also form a tower. (By `ringHomEquivModuleIsScalarTower` in #9381, there is therefore a canonical RingHom from R to S.)

+ Lemmas for free modules over rings including `finrank_mul_finrank'` are moved from FieldTheory/Tower to LinearAlgebra/Dimension/Free

[Zulip](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/Puzzle.3A.20noncommutative.20RingHom.20as.20typeclasses/near/407347711)

nodes.body: @erdOne Is this related to what you are doing?
No, but this is probably yet another misplaced lemma.

Yeah the lemma `cardinal_lift_le_rank_of_linearIndependent` directly follows from the definition, so it probably should be placed right below the def. I've now used a corollary of it (`LinearIndependent.finrank_eq_zero_of_infinite`) to remove StrongRankCondition from the series of lemmas starting from [finrank_eq_zero_of_basis_imp_not_finite](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/Finrank.html#finrank_eq_zero_of_basis_imp_not_finite). Maybe the change is also in your PR? I haven't got time to look it through yet.
I assumed `StrongRankCondition R` almost everywhere so probably not.
!bench

Here are the [benchmark results](http://speed.lean-fro.org/mathlib4/run-detail/2f76436c-d9ce-4917-8835-335c573eef85) for commit f36ebb9ed17fcf12db34f00534824dafe7680ae0.
There were [no significant changes](http://speed.lean-fro.org/mathlib4/compare/b2865b79-b2da-4bc2-8162-2e6513037700/to/2f76436c-d9ce-4917-8835-335c573eef85) against commit f7c6fc158c0e23f2d8ae5731b7f2f5507901297a.
Since there has been inaction on this PR, I'm splitting this into smaller PRs in the hope that other reviewers might more easily weigh in.
Thanks to @jcommelin for merging two dependency PRs; now this PR reduces to two files and is therefore marked easy.

> Is the description of the PR up-to-date with the current status?

Yes, I recently edited the description.

> Also I don't if this was made on purpose, but I don't see the modifications added with [23ceeb5](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/9046/commits/23ceeb5810d2f6bb7d6a897eb876328fae6781f0)

I removed the division-ring specialized version, so only the Module.Free version remains. See [here](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/9046#discussion_r1444164388).

Thanks!

Isn't this `span_induction`?

This one only need the R-multiples of elements in the generating set to satisfy the predicate, rather than R-multiples of all elements satisfying the predicate. The condition H2 is easier to verify when proving `span_smul_of_span_eq_top` (I'm not aware of a way proving it without the commutativity assumption without going through `closure_induction`).
Maybe put your explanation into a docstring?

```suggestion
    [AddCommMonoid M] [AddCommMonoid N] [SMul R M] [SMul R N] [Module S M] [Module S N]
```

Not sure why this can't be an instance? All four variables appear in the goal. Is it due to the outParams?
(This can't be to_additivized as the VAddHom(Class) doesn't exist ...)
I believe it is because they are outparams?
Okay I think I get how it works: one F is supposed to correspond to one M' only. Not very flexible! X and Y certainly should be outParams but maybe M' could be an autoParam instead?
Does autoParam work in instances? Anyway I think such instances are probably out of scope of what `SMulHomClass` was trying to achieve.
Thanks indeed the docs for [autoParam](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Init/Meta.html#autoParam) says it won't affect typeclass resolution like optParam.

```suggestion
/-- If Y/X/M forms a scalar tower, any map X â†’ Y preserving X-action also preserves M-action. -/
```
What's with these regressions? (also the `rfl` below and the instance in `Mathlib/RingTheory/Kaehler.lean`)
This is a generalization (from CommSemiring/Algebra to Ring/Module), not a regression. The need of an additional rfl below is strange though.

This regression is strange. Somehow after `rw [â† LinearMap.map_smul_of_tower]`, Lean suddenly needs to be reminded of the SMulZeroClass instance, otherwise it can't `rw Finsupp.smul_single`. `map_smul_of_tower` consumes a `LinearMap.CompatibleSMul` instance, so maybe due to the new instances introduced, the rw produces a syntactically slightly different result. I think it's a pretty well-known bug that Lean has trouble inferring weaker instances from stronger ones, e.g. Algebra to Module to SMul. (Maybe it matters whether the stronger `extend`s the weaker one?)
Does it timeout or fail?
I think it's a fail (says it can't synthesize `SMulZeroClass R S`)
That is strange. The well-known bug (that I know of) just times out.

I think the three instance reminders [here](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/8aa9689f0e48c6fcf9b3ad6846b722c13b7fcd53/Mathlib/RingTheory/IntegralClosure.lean#L855-L862) are all failures.

Oh no, the first one apparently is a timeout according to the comment. The last one looks like Lean goes down a wrong path and eventually fails.

My impression is that this mostly happens with subobjects, Subalgebra there, and [KaehlerDifferential.kerTotal](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/RingTheory/Kaehler.html#KaehlerDifferential.kerTotal) here is a Submodule (but R and S in the SMulZeroClass aren't).
The comment says it times out though. Anyways I'm still waiting for the cache so I can check it out myself.

Sorry, I just checked and you're right; all those three instances come with a message
> (deterministic) timeout at 'typeclass', maximum number of heartbeats (20000) has been reached (use 'set_option synthInstance.maxHeartbeats <num>' to set the limit)

while this timeout in Kaehler does not.

I just compared the context and the goal state after `rw [â† LinearMap.map_smul_of_tower]` on master against this PR, with pp.all turned on. It turns out they are completely identical, so I'm completely dumbfounded why Lean suddenly needs the reminder ...
I looked into it myself and it seems like some strange bug in the synthesizer that is probably not this PR's fault.

Maybe you've seen it, but in case not, let me mention that I tried to add shortcut instances over subobjects (IntermediateField in this case) in #9291 and they have been effective in avoiding timeouts or manual `haveI/letI`s.

```suggestion
/-- A variant of `span_induction` that combines `âˆ€ x âˆˆ s, p x` and `âˆ€ r x, p x â†’ p (r â€¢ x)`
into a single condition `âˆ€ r, âˆ€ x âˆˆ s, p (r â€¢ x)`, which can be easier to verify. -/
@[elab_as_elim]
theorem closure_induction {p : M â†’ Prop} (h : x âˆˆ span R s) (H0 : p 0)
    (H1 : âˆ€ x y, p x â†’ p y â†’ p (x + y)) (H2 : âˆ€ r : R, âˆ€ x âˆˆ s, p (r â€¢ x)) : p x := by
```
Can you write the dependent version instead, since that one works with the `induction` tactic?
Sure, will do! Bu why can't `induction` work with non-dependent versions?
I'm somewhat skeptical of the value of these instances, or even of the `LinearMap.CompatibleSMul` typeclass itself. Are they actually needed by this PR?

It's needed in (the generalization of) `Basis.smul`, which depends on `Basis.isScalarTower_finsupp`, which depends on `isScalarTower_of_injective`, which consumes a `LinearMap.CompatibleSMul` instance that is supplied by `LinearMap.CompatibleSMul.finsupp_dom` together with `IsScalarTower.compatibleSMul'`. `finsupp_cod` and this one (`.pi`) are not used, but I think there is no harm adding them according to the benchmark. Probably there aren't much (or any) instances that consume CompatibleSMul but do not also output CompatibleSMul?

Similar to a [previous commit](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/9046/commits/0478370c1e2c9c6212f8f714fd2503f7094c80ad) I've changed lemma names to make available LinearIndependent dot notations in this file as well (including some new lemmas introduced by @erdOne in #8872). If I split these as a dependent PR it could reduce "files changed" by 4~5 files.

```
[3992/4084] Buildierror: > LEAN_PATH=./.lake/packages/std/.lake/build/lib:./.lake/packages/Qq/.lake/build/lib:./.lake/packages/aesop/.lake/build/lib:./.lake/packages/proofwidgets/.lake/build/lib:./.lake/packages/Cli/.lake/build/lib:./.lake/build/lib LD_LIBRARY_PATH=./.lake/build/lib /home/lean/.elan/toolchains/leanprover--lean4---v4.5.0-rc1/bin/lean -Dpp.unicode.fun=true -Dpp.proofs.withType=false -DautoImplicit=false -DrelaxedAutoImplicit=false ./././Mathlib/FieldTheory/PolynomialGaloisGroup.lean -R ././. -o ./.lake/build/lib/Mathlib/FieldTheory/PolynomialGaloisGroup.olean -i ./.lake/build/lib/Mathlib/FieldTheory/PolynomialGaloisGroup.ilean -c ./.lake/build/ir/Mathlib/FieldTheory/PolynomialGaloisGroup.c

```
the line is `rw [â† FiniteDimensional.finrank_mul_finrank F FâŸ®Î±âŸ¯ p.SplittingField,`
I guess it's the well-known problem that Lean fails to synthesize `AddCommGroup FâŸ®Î±âŸ¯` from stronger classes for subobjects like `FâŸ®Î±âŸ¯`. It looks for `AddCommGroup` because there's a `Module.Free` condition in `finrank_mul_finrank'` which is not present (automatic) in `finrank_mul_finrank`. I'll add a docstring to explain this.

> (maybe that should be unprimed and this be called something like finrank_mul_finrank_of_field)

I think I'd rather rename `finrank_mul_finrank'` to `finrank_mul_finrank_of_free`. Would you like me to do that?

couldn't a `letI` or a `maxHeartbeat` fix that?
I still think the ring version should be the main lemma as it is strictly more general and mirrors `rank_mul_rank`.

Okay, I'm [trying this again](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/9046/commits/f87e8a4383095ab8f9fab65adb9cccac6979b3de) by fixing the timeout with `letI _ : AddCommGroup FâŸ®Î±âŸ¯ := Ring.toAddCommGroup`. Hopefully no other errors pop up. But why not keep a lemma that is easier to use (can be used with less manual instances)?

First of all it shouldn't have needed manual instances. It is a bug and hopefully will be fixed.
Second, I'm not totally against such duplication, but like `FiniteDimensional.finrank_eq_rank'`, but I think the duplication should be primed and the docstring should clearly say that it is a duplication for performance reasons.

```suggestion
`dim_F(A) = dim_F(K) * dim_K(A)`. 
  A special case of `FiniteDimensional.finrank_mul_finrank'` which assumes `Module.Free`.
We keep this because Lean sometimes has trouble finding the `Module.Free` instances. -/
```

```suggestion `dim_F(A) = dim_F(K) * dim_K(A)`. ```
Can you add a comment saying that sooner or later this line should be removed?

Maybe we should create an issue to track this problem of failing to find weaker instances from strong instances on subobjects, so we can refer to the issue here and elsewhere, which will make it easy to remove all these `letI/haveI`s once the issue is resolved?
Can you add a comment saying that sooner or later those lines should be removed?
For this one, there's already a porting note. I simply extracted the two arguments in the original `rw` to standalone `letI`s.
Can you add a reference to `rank_mul_rank` below?

Like this?
```suggestion
$\operatorname{rank}_F(A) = \operatorname{rank}_F(K) * \operatorname{rank}_K(A)$.

The universe polymorphic version of `rank_mul_rank` below. -/
```
